\section Example2

The "evalsensor" documentation describes the process of grouping the nodes
of a water network into different classes, where the nodes in a given class
have the same probability of giving a false negative reading.   The "sc"
file defines the false negative probability of each class, and the "jc" 
(junction class) file maps node ids to failure classes.

Before defining these failure classes, let us repeat a simple experiment:
finding the mean extent of contamination for our epanet test network in the
test directory:

\verbatim
../../../bin/sp --path=../../../bin --path=../mod --network=test1 --objective=ec --ub=ns,5 --solver=heuristic

Number of Contamination Events:  97
Number of Contamination Impacts: 9430

Validating input for heuristic solver
Number of sensors=5
Objective=ec
Statistic=mean
Impact file=/home/wehart/src/spot/spot-1.0/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.impact
Delay=0
Running iterated descent heuristic for *perfect* sensor model
Iterated descent completed - sensors written to file=test1.sensors
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        846930886
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            19 28 54 63 75
Sensor junctions:           119 141 193 207 239

Impact File:                /home/wehart/src/spot/spot-1.0/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                8418.7979
Lower quartile impact:      0.0000
Median impact:              6949.0000
Upper quartile impact:      12530.0000
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 25960.0000
TCE                 (  5%): 33323.2833
Max impact:                 42994.8000
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\endverbatim

The test.imperfectsc file defines a set of false-negative classes:  

\verbatim
$ more test1.imperfectsc
1 0.25
2 0.50
3 0.75
4 1.0
\endverbatim

Sensors of class "1" give false negative readings 25% of the time, sensors
of class "2" give them 50% of the time, etc.  

Once failure classes have been defined, the nodes of the network are assigned
to classes.  This is done with another file (a "junction class" or jc file).
The test1.imperfectjc file maps nodes to classes:

\verbatim
$ head -20 test1.imperfectjc
1 1
2 1
3 1
4 1
5 1
6 1
7 1
8 1
9 1
10 1
11 1
12 1
13 1
14 1
15 1
16 1
17 1
18 1
19 1
20 1
\endverbatim

Given the node classes, we may run evalsensor again to determine the
expected impact of a sensor placement, given that sensors may fail.  Using
the solution just found:

\verbatim
../../../bin/evalsensor --sc-probabilities=test1.imperfectsc --scs=test1.imperfectjc test1.sensors test1_ec.impact
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        846930886
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            19 28 54 63 75
Sensor junctions:

Impact File:                test1_ec.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                17075.1369
Lower quartile impact:      3940.0000
Median impact:              14952.2500
Upper quartile impact:      26486.7938
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 47554.5742
TCE                 (  5%): 54893.8613
Max impact:                 75426.7012
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\endverbatim

So the "perfect-sensor" solution of 8478.97 pipe feet of contamination is
quite misleading if sensors truly fail according to the probabilities we
have assigned.

However, we may optimize with these failure probabilities in mind.  The
results are shown next:

\verbatim
../../../bin/sp --path=../../../bin --path=../mod --network=test1 --objective=ec --ub=ns,5 --imperfect-scfile=test1.imperfectsc --imperfect-jcfile=test1.imperfectjc --solver=heuristic

