\section Example4

The examples above dealt with the "extent of contamination" objective.
How well do the sensor placements generated above minimize the expected mass
of contaminant consumed over all modeled events?  First we will call 
evalsensor with the solution to Example3, which is now stored in 
test1.sensors:

\verbatim
../../../bin/evalsensor test1.sensors test1_mc.impact
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        846930886
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            17 19 24 65 88
Sensor junctions:

Impact File:                test1_mc.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                70895.2854
Lower quartile impact:      503.9170
Median impact:              83150.7000
Upper quartile impact:      144002.0000
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 144271.0000
TCE                 (  5%): 144546.8333
Max impact:                 144693.0000
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\endverbatim

The mean mass consumed is 70,895.2854, which is far from optimal.  Suppose that
we know from previous runs that the optimal solution for the mean mass consumed problem on this ensemble is roughly 22,000 units.  Keeping "extent of 
contamination - tce" as our primary objective, we can now impose a 
"side constraint" that precludes any solution that admits an average 
mass consumed of worse than 30,000 units.  We do this as follows:

\verbatim
../../../bin/sp --path=../../../bin  --network=test1 --objective=ec_tce --ub=mc_mean,30000 --ub=ns,5 --solver=heuristic

Number of Contamination Events:  97
Number of Contamination Impacts: 9430

Validating input for heuristic solver
Number of sensors=5
Objective=ec
Statistic=tce
Impact file=/home/wehart/src/spot/spot-1.0/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.impact
Delay=0
Running iterated descent heuristic for *perfect* sensor model
Iterated descent completed - sensors written to file=test1.sensors
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        1681692777
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            4 15 29 68 81
Sensor junctions:           35 111 143 215 253

Impact File:                /home/wehart/src/spot/spot-1.0/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                14255.3627
Lower quartile impact:      1379.0000
Median impact:              10660.0000
Upper quartile impact:      21809.8000
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 37915.8000
TCE                 (  5%): 48340.3667
Max impact:                 71329.0000

Impact File:                /home/wehart/src/spot/spot-1.0/packages/sp/test/test1_mc.impact
Number of events:           236
Min impact:                 0.0000
Mean impact:                29501.3233
Lower quartile impact:      139.0200
Median impact:              1766.1000
Upper quartile impact:      16476.3000
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 144271.0000
TCE                 (  5%): 144276.3333
Max impact:                 144335.0000
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
\endverbatim


Note that the primary objective, minimizing the TCE of the 
"extent of contamination" measure, has gotten worse:  it is now 48340.3667
rather than 43162.9073.  However, our side constraint has
been honored, and the mean mass consumed value is now 29501.3233 rather than
70895.2854.

The process of multi-objective optimization is currently an iterative one
in which the values of the side constraints are varied.  A more general
multi-objective capabilty would explore the "pareto front" of optimal 
trade-offs between objectives.  However, such a search would 
clearly be expensive to perform.




\section Example5

NOTE: these experiments need to be updated to reflect the new aggregation 
measures, and to discuss the valid lower bound that is computed.

Now, consider the IP robustness measure offerred by sp: "CVaR," or 
"Conditional Value at Risk."  Without going into technical details, consider
this to be an approximation to TCE that can be modeled conveniently.  CVaR
can be exceptionally hard to solve in practice, so it may not be possible
to place bounds on the solutions generated by larger analogues to Examples
2 and 3 above.

It is very hard to solve our current formulation of "CVaR," but we can use
"witness aggregation" to shrink the problem and obtain an approximate soution
much more quickly.  First, consider once more our "extent of contamination
instance, and let us try to solve the model for the globally optimal 
"CVaR" measure.

\verbatim
$ ../../../bin/sp --path=../../../bin  --path=../mod --network=test1 --objective=ec_cvar --ub=ns,5 --solver=pico

Setting up IP data file...
Running PICO...
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        30043
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            17 19 88 65 24
Sensor junctions:           115 119 267 209 127

Impact File:                /reservoir1/teva/teva-sp/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.
mpact
Number of events          : 236
Min impact:                 0
Mean impact:                10266.1
Lower quartile impact:      0
Median impact:              10400
Upper quartile impact:      16930
Value at Risk (VaR) (  5%): 24199
TCE                 (  5%): 26376.2
Max impact:                 28564.8
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5077.49user 74.92system 1:26:02elapsed 99%CPU (0avgtext+0avgdata 0maxresident)k
0inputs+0outputs (0major+15984373minor)pagefaults 0swaps

\endverbatim

Note that this solve took almost two hours.  For large networks, this problem
would become intractable.  

However, let us explore "witness aggregation."  The witness list of an event
is a list of nodes ordered by the first time they experience contamination.
For a simplified example, suppose that for event 1, the witness list is 
1,2,3,4.  Suppose further that the global extent of contamination at the 
respective times these nodes are hit is 10, 15, 20, and 25. And finally, 
suppose that the 25 unit impact is the worst over all events.  We may set
a "threshold" of 50 percent (12.5 units) and group witnesses into classes
based on this threshold.  In our example, witnesses 1 and 2 become one
"super witness" with impact 15, and witnesses 3 and 4 become another super
witness with impact 25.  The witness list is now only half as long, and
when we solve the problem we will have a conservative solution that 
overestimates the true impacts (since, for example, true witness 1 is 
charged a conservative 15 units of impact rather than its true value of 10).

Returning to our CVaR example, let us run it one more time with a witness
aggregation threshold of 0.125 (12.5 percent):

\verbatim
$ ../../../bin/sp --path=../../../bin  --path=../mod --network=test1 --objective=ec_cvar --percent=ec,0.125 --ub=ns,5 --solver=pico

Setting up IP data file...
Running PICO...
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Sensor placement id:        30014
Number of sensors:          5
Total cost:                 0
Sensor node IDs:            17 19 54 63 24
Sensor junctions:           115 119 193 207 127

Impact File:                /reservoir1/teva/teva-sp/packages/sp/test/test1_ec.i
mpact
Number of events          : 236
Min impact:                 0
Mean impact:                9624.81
